From e6fe4b9c2d31c54dcbb67e4d505c93fd6c87a816 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: John Wiegley <johnw@newartisans.com>
Date: Wed, 15 Jul 2026 16:48:37 -0700
Subject: [PATCH] fix(codex): gate hook rebinds and fork subagent-thread
 bindings

Codex refuses user-initiated turns on any thread whose session_meta says
thread_source=subagent: `codex resume` loads such a thread and even
auto-continues goal-mode work, but the first typed message makes the TUI
exit status 1 with "Error: turn/start failed in TUI", killing the tmux
session in an error loop (2026-07-15 ares fleet incident).

Sessions end up bound to subagent threads two ways:

- Poisoning: subagent threads fire the same agent-turn-complete notify
  hook as the main thread, and bindCodexSessionFromHook accepted any
  payload id with no quality gate (unlike the Claude clear-rebind
  heuristics), so a completing child usurped the binding and the next
  restart resumed it.
- Adoption: an earlier mid-flight restart resumed a subagent thread
  directly; the session runs goal-mode work fine but dies the moment an
  operator sends it a message.

Two defenses, both reading the bound rollout's session_meta head:

- Hook gate: reject rebinds to thread_source=subagent rollouts, with a
  lifecycle reject event. Unflushed candidates still bind (fail-open).
- Restart safety net: buildCodexCommand launches subagent-sourced
  bindings with `codex fork <sid>` instead of `codex resume <sid>`. The
  fork carries the thread's full context into a fresh
  thread_source=user thread that accepts input, and the live-process
  probe rebinds the instance to the fork's new id once it is up.

Co-Authored-By: Claude Fable 5 <noreply@anthropic.com>
